{
  "doc_id": "20727",
  "text": "The latest Cretaceous and earliest Paleocene Ginkgo adiantoides fossils were obtained by loan from the Denver Museum of Nature and Science and the Yale Peabody Museum, respectively. The Cretaceous fossils come from the Hell Creek Formation in the Williston Basin of North Dakota (Denver Museum of Nature and Science site 566), 33.5 m below the K-Pg boundary [CITATION_1] . Based on constraints from geochronology, magnetostratigraphy, and sedimentation rates, [CITATION_2] consider the locality 0.5 Myr older than the K-Pg boundary. The early Paleocene fossils come from the Fort Union Formation in the Bighorn Basin of Wyoming (Yale Peabody Museum site 7659), 4 m above the K-Pg boundary; based on sedimentation rates, [CITATION_3] interpret the site to postdate the K-Pg boundary by 0.5 Myr. We assume a K-Pg boundary age of 66 Ma [CITATION_4] [CITATION_5] .",
